> I'm assuming that "take off angle" is what is shown in more detail on
> a graph usually named: "vertical plane radiation pattern". - Please
> correct me if this is wrong.  I once asked a question regarding the
> take-off angle of a beam antenna - Specifically: Can I vary the
> take-off angle (or vertical plane radiation pattern) by tilting the
> boom of a beam (so that the director is higher than the driven
> element, for example.)  The answer I got was: "No."  On the other hand
> I've read that the vertical plane radiation pattern of a full wave
> loop, as one example, certainly changes when it is flipped from
> perpendicular to the ground to parallel to the ground.  Surely it must
> have a continuum of various vertical plane radiation patterns as it is
> turned from perpendicular to parallel. (???)  What am I missing here?
> Should I have used the term: "vertical plane radiation pattern",
> rather than "take-off angle" in my original question??  Does a full
> wave loop vary as described, but not a beam?  I'll be grateful for a
> clarification.
